history.content: I took it last semester and found the workload wasn't too bad aside from a group debate that you have to prepare near the end. Discussion attendance is mandatory. The first half of the class is lecture with reading assignments, and the second half is just listening to group debates. There are occasional in class quizzes, but half of our final was take home, which was really easy.

children.subject: Readings are pretty necessary, the professor covers the general topics that each chapter covers but the quizzes/final exam ask questions that would typically require you to have read the book.
Oh and there's also a weekly assignment that you have to write ~1 page reflection on.
But there's no guarantee that the class in the fall will be run like it was last semester, given the fact that most of the class was upset with the way the class was run (bad course evals).

That sounds like more work than I'm looking for. Are the readings necessary to do well in the quizzes and/or on the final? I've usually never done the readings for any non-techs (nor for techs most of the time lol).

history.content: Is BioE 100 worth taking over CS 195 if you just need to satisfy the ethics requirement? I know the former is graded while the latter is P/NP, and while the curve seems pretty generous for BioE 100, with it being 3 units compared to CS 195 being only 1 unit, I was wondering if it was a lot more work? I would like the units and would not mind a nice little GPA boost, but don't really want to put in effort into the ethics requirement of all things for those benefits.
